# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: defensive-spectrum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A **baseball field**, also called a **ball field** or **baseball diamond**, is the field upon which the game of baseball is played.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The term can also be used as a metonym for a baseball park.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The term **sandlot** is sometimes used, although this usually refers to less organized venues for activities like sandlot ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The starting point for much of the action on the field is home plate (officially "home base"), a five-sided slab of white rubber.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] One side is 17 inches (43 cm) long, the two adjacent sides are 8.5 inches (22 cm).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The remaining two sides are approximately 12 inches (30 cm) and set at a right angle.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The plate is set into the ground so that its surface is level with the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The corner of home plate where the two 12-inch sides meet at a right angle is at one corner of a 90-foot (27.43 m) square.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The dimensional specifications are technically inconsistent because the angle constraints require that the front be √2 times the length of the back, which is not equal to a 17:12 ratio, but a physically built home plate will have side lengths accurate to a few hundredths of an inch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The other three corners of the square, in counterclockwise order from home plate, are called first, second, and third base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] These bases are marked by canvas or rubber cushions, 18 inches (46 cm) square and 3–5 inches (7.6–12.7 cm) thick.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Adjacent to each of the two parallel 8.5-inch sides is a batter's box.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] All the bases, including home plate, lie entirely within fair territory.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Thus, any batted ball that touches those bases must necessarily be ruled a fair ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] While the first and third base bags are placed so that they lie inside the 90-foot square formed by the bases, the second base bag is placed so that its center (unlike first, third and home) coincides exactly with the "point" of the ninety-foot square.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Thus, although the "points" of the bases are 90 feet apart, the physical distance between each successive pair of base markers is closer to 88 feet (26.8 m).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Near the center of the square is an artificial hill known as the pitcher's mound, atop which is a white rubber slab known as the pitcher's plate, colloquially the "rubber" because of its physical composition.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The specifications for the pitcher's mound are described below.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The lines from home plate to first and third bases extend to the nearest fence, stand or other obstruction and are called the foul lines.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The portion of the playing field between (and including) the foul lines is fair territory; the rest is "foul territory".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The area within the square formed by the bases is officially called the infield, though colloquially this term also includes fair territory in the vicinity of the square; fair territory outside the infield is known as the outfield.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Most baseball fields are enclosed with a fence that marks the outer edge of the outfield.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The fence is usually set at a distance ranging from 300 to 420 feet (90 to 130 m) from home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Most professional and college baseball fields have a right and left foul pole which are about 440 to 500 feet (130 to 150 m) apart.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] These poles are at the intersection of the foul lines and the respective ends of the outfield fence and, unless otherwise specified within the ground rules, lie in fair territory.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Thus, a batted ball that passes over the outfield wall in flight and touches the foul pole is a fair ball and the batter is awarded a home run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A baseball infield is the square area within the four 90-foot baselines "(60-foot baselines in Little League Baseball for youths 12 years old and under)".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The four bases are integral parts of the infield; a ball that touches any part of a base is considered a fair ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] First base is the first of the four bases that must be touched by a runner in order to score a run for the batting team.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The runner may continue running past first base in a straight line without being in jeopardy of being put out, so long as they make contact with first base and make no move or attempt to advance to second base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The first baseman is the defensive player mainly responsible for the area near first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In some youth leagues and adult recreational leagues, a "double first base" or "safety first base" is used.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A double first base is rectangular (rather than square), measuring 30 by 15 inches.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It is normally colored white and orange (two 15 by 15 inches squares).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It is placed with the white half in fair territory and the orange half in foul territory.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The white half is used by the first baseman to make plays while the orange half is used by the runner.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This creates a separation between the first baseman and runner, reducing the chance of injury on plays at first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the first baseman is assigned the number 3.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Second base is the second of the four bases a runner must touch in order to score a run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Second base is mainly defended by the second baseman and the shortstop.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The second baseman and shortstop ideally possess quick reactions and the ability to release the ball rapidly and accurately.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] One player will usually cover second base while the other attempts to field the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Both players must communicate well to be able to make a double play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Particular agility is required of the second baseman in many double play situations, which frequently force the player receiving a throw from the shortstop to immediately throw towards first base while their momentum typically carries them towards third base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A runner on second base is said to be in "scoring position", since there is a higher likelihood of scoring a run from second base on a single than there is from first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Since second base is the farthest from home plate, it is the most commonly stolen base in baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the second baseman is assigned the number 4, and the shortstop 6.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Third base is the third of the four bases a runner must touch in order to score a run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The third baseman is the defensive player mainly responsible for the area nearest third base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A third baseman ideally possesses quick reaction to batted balls and a strong throwing arm to make the long throw to first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Third base is sometimes referred to as the "hot corner" as it's common for right-handed batters to hit the ball hard to third base, occasionally making successfully fielding the ball difficult.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the third baseman is assigned the number 5.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Like a runner on second base, a runner on third base is said to be in "scoring position", since there is a higher likelihood of scoring a run on any hit, a sacrifice fly, and many other plays, provided that the third and final out is not recorded before they can reach home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Home base, called "home plate", is the final base that a player must touch to score a run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Unlike the other bases, home plate is a five-sided slab of white rubber that is set at ground level.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In most MLB stadiums, the backstop is at least 60 feet behind home plate and is composed of a lower solid wall and upper netting that protects spectators behind home plate from wild pitches, passed balls, and foul balls.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In recreational fields, there is usually a tall chain-link fence that surrounds the infield and the players' bench for player safety.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Baselines are straight lines between two adjacent bases normally made of chalk.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Physical baselines are not drawn between first and second or second and third bases; the foul lines serve to mark the baseline between home plate and first base, and between third base and home.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Generally, baserunners are not required to follow the baseline.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A baserunner seeking to advance more than one base typically "rounds" the base, following a more circular path.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] However, a runner's avoidance maneuvers are constrained when the defense tries to tag him.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] At the moment the defense begins the attempt, the baserunner's running baseline is established as a direct line from his current position to the base he is trying for.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A runner straying more than three feet (1 m) away from this baseline to avoid a tag may be called out.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Beginning halfway between home and first base, and ending at first base, there is a second chalk line to the right of the foul line.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This second line and the part of the foul line it runs parallel to, form the running lane that defines the path in which a batter-runner must run as he is advancing to first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Rule 6.05(k) of the Official Baseball Rules states that if a batter-runner running to first base runs outside the running lane, and "in doing so" interferes with the fielder taking the throw at first, then the batter-runner is automatically out.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] First base itself is not located in the running lane, but Rule 6.05 lets the batter-runner leave the running lane "by means of a step, stride or slide in the immediate vicinity of first base" to step on first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The batter's box is the place where the batter stands when ready to receive a pitch from the pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It is usually drawn in chalk on the dirt surrounding home plate, and the insides of the boxes are watered down before each game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The chalk lines delineating the two foul lines are rarely extended through the batter's boxes.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] However, those lines exist conceptually for the purpose of judging a batted ball fair or foul.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In addition, inside edges of the batter's boxes are often not laid-in with chalk.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Similarly, though not marked, those lines continue to exist for the purpose of the rules pertaining to the batter's box and the batter's position relative thereto.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] There are two batter's boxes, one on each side of home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The batter's boxes are 4 feet (1.22 m) wide and 6 feet (1.83 m) long.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The batter's boxes are centered lengthwise at the center of home plate with the inside line of each batter's box 6 inches (15 cm) from the near edge of home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A right-handed batter would stand in the batter's box on the right side of home plate from the perspective of the pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A left-handed batter would stand in the batter's box to their left.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A batter may only occupy one batter's box at a time and may not legally leave the batter's box after the pitcher has come set or has started their windup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Should the batter wish to leave the batter's box once the pitcher has engaged the rubber, they must first ask the umpire for time-out.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Time will not be granted if the pitcher has already started their pitching motion.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] For playing rules relating to the batter's box, see Rules 6.05 and 6.06 of the Official Baseball Rules.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The catcher's box is an area of the field behind home plate which the catcher occupies to avoid committing a balk when a pitch is thrown.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In roughly the middle of the diamond, equidistant between first and third base, and a few feet closer to home plate than to second base, is a low artificial hill called the pitcher's mound.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This is where the pitcher stands when throwing the pitch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Atop the mound is a white rubber slab, called the pitcher's plate or pitcher's rubber.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It measures 6 inches (15 cm) front-to-back and 2 feet (61 cm) across, the front of which is exactly 60 feet 6 inches (18.44 m) from the rear point of home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This peculiar distance was set by the rule makers in 1893, not due to a clerical or surveying error as popular myth has it, but intentionally (further details under *History*).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In Major League Baseball, a regulation mound is 18 feet (5.5 m) in diameter, with the center 59 feet (18 m) from the rear point of home plate, on the line between home plate and second base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The front edge of the *pitcher's plate* or *rubber* is 18 inches (46 cm) behind the center of the mound, making the front edge's midpoint 60 feet 6 inches from the rear point of home plate. six inches (15 cm) in front of the pitcher's rubber the mound begins to slope downward.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The top of the rubber is to be no higher than ten inches (25 cm) above home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] From 1903 through 1968, this height limit was set at 15 inches (38 cm), but in reality differed from ballpark to ballpark as the height was considered too difficult to enforce.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A higher mound generally favors the pitcher, and teams that emphasize pitching (such as the Los Angeles Dodgers) will favor a slightly higher mound.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] With the height advantage, the pitcher gains more leverage and can put more downward velocity on the ball, making it more difficult for the batter to strike the ball squarely with the bat.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] After 1968, known among baseball historians as "the year of the pitcher", the official height of the mound was lowered from 15 to 10 inches (38 to 25 cm) in an attempt to "increase the batting" once again.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A pitcher's mound is difficult for groundskeepers to maintain.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Usually before every game it is watered down to keep the dust from spreading.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] On youth and amateur baseball fields, the mound may be much different from the rule book definition due to erosion and repair attempts.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Even in the major leagues, each mound gains its own character, as pitchers are allowed to kick away pieces of dirt in their way, thereby sculpting the mound a bit to their preference.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The pitcher may keep a rosin bag on the rear of the mound to dry off their hands.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Major League Baseball teams are also permitted cleat cleaners on the back of the mound.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This may be a flat grate-style plate, or simply a hand tool such as a piece of wood used to remove mud and dirt from cleats.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] These items are allowed to remain on the backside of the mound at the discretion of the umpire, thus reducing the probability that they will affect a live play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Dirt running paths between the bases (and at one time, and still in some parks, between the pitcher and the catcher) have existed since the beginning of the game, although they were not mentioned in the rule books until around 1950, and their specifications are flexible.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In addition to providing a running path, the grass lines act as a visual aid so that players, umpires and fans may better judge distance from the center of the diamond.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Occasionally the ball may take a tricky bounce off the dirt area or the edge between the dirt and the grass.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Multiple World Series championships (including 1924 and 1960) have been influenced by erratic hops of ground balls.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In artificial turf stadiums, infield dirt was originally only placed in three five-sided areas around the bases and in two circles around the pitcher's and batting areas, which are referred to as "cutouts".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In this configuration, the "grass line" is usually designated with a white arc.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This setup first appeared at Cincinnati's Riverfront Stadium upon its opening in 1970.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Among Major League Baseball fields, Rogers Centre was the last stadium to maintain this type of configuration and was reconfigured with a full dirt infield starting in the 2016 MLB season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In some college baseball parks with artificial turf fields, the entire field (along with possibly the pitcher's mound) is made up of turf, with parts of the field mainly containing dirt instead merely being clay-colored turf.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The outfield is made from shortly-trimmed grass or artificial turf.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The positions to play in the outfield are left, center, and right field (named in relation to the batter's position; thus left field is beyond third base and right field is beyond first base).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Outfields vary in size and shape depending on the overall size and shape of the playing field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The outfield stretches from the infield to the outfield wall and it contains the warning track.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Outfields especially vary from Little League to major league fields.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Little League outfields vary more in size than Major League outfields.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Outfields often differ from infields in the specific type of grass used, but most major league outfields are grass.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The warning track is the strip of dirt at the edges of the baseball field (especially in front of the home run fence and along the left and right sides of a field).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Because the warning track's color and feel differ from the grass field, a fielder can remain focused on a fly ball near the fence and measure their proximity to the fence while attempting to catch the ball safely.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A warning track's width is not specified in the rules.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It is generally designed to give about three steps of warning to the highest-level players using the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Typical widths run from about six feet for Little League fields to about 10–15 feet (3.0–4.6 meters) for college- or professional-level play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] A warning track this wide also lets groundskeepers avoid driving maintenance vehicles on the grass.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The track can be composed of finely ground rock particles such as cinders, which is why announcer Bob Wolff called it the "cinder path" rather than the "warning track".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The idea of a warning track originated in Yankee Stadium, where an actual running track was built for use in track and field events.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] When ballpark designers saw how the track helped fielders, it soon became a feature of every ballpark.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Fielders often knowingly risk injury crashing into a wall trying to make a catch despite the warning track.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] For this reason, outfield walls are typically padded for extra safety.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Wrigley Field's brick wall is covered only by ivy, which is not especially soft.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] However, there are pads on the walls of the tight left and right field corners in foul ground.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The outfield wall or fence is the outer boundary of the outfield.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] If it passes over the wall in fair territory, without touching the ground, it is a home run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] As a result, baseball fields can vary greatly along those lines.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The wall has numbers affixed or painted on it that denote the distance from that point on the wall to home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In most modern major league ballparks, the wall is made of some hard material (e.g., concrete, plywood, sheet metal) with padding on the field side to protect players who may collide with the wall at high speed while trying to make a play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Chain link fencing may also be incorporated into the wall in areas where the wall needs to be transparent, e.g., an outfield bullpen, a spectator area behind the wall, or to protect a scoreboard incorporated into the wall.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Many ballparks feature a yellow line denoting the top of the wall to aid umpires in judging whether the ball passed over the wall or if the ball is fair or foul.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Foul poles, if present, help umpires judge whether a fly ball hit above the fence line is foul (out of play) or fair (a home run).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The poles are a vertical extension of the foul lines at the edge of the field of play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The outer edge of the foul lines and foul poles define foul territory.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] **Both the lines and the poles are actually in fair territory**, in contrast to American football and basketball, where the lines marking the playing boundaries are out of bounds.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The minimum distance to hit a home run (along either foul line) is set by baseball rules, generally at 325 feet (99 m).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Before 1931 (with the exception of a couple months in 1920) the foul lines extended indefinitely; a batter was awarded a home run only if a fly ball out of the field was fair where it landed.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Now, a batted ball that leaves the field in flight is judged fair or foul at the point it leaves the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Thus, such a fly ball passing on the fair side of a foul pole, or hitting a foul pole, is a home run regardless of where the ball goes thereafter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Foul poles are typically much higher than the top of the outfield fence or wall, and often have a narrow screen running along the fair side of the pole.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This further aids the umpires' judgment, as a ball that bounces off this screen is a home run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It can still be a difficult call, especially in ballparks with no outfield stands behind the poles to provide perspective.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Wrigley Field is notorious for arguments over long, curving flies down a foul line (most notably in left field) that sail higher than the foul pole.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] At Major League Baseball fields, foul poles are usually yellow.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] At Petco Park, there is no foul pole in left field; the pole's function is served by a yellow metal strip along the corner of the Western Metal Supply Co. building.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Several parks featuring advertising along the length of the foul pole, with the most prominent example being the advertising from Chick-fil-A at both Citi Field and Daikin Park (serving as a pun, with "fowl" being another term for a chicken, the primary meat featured by that restaurant chain).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The bullpen (sometimes referred to as simply "the 'pen") is the area where pitchers warm up before entering a game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Depending on the ballpark, it may be situated in foul territory along the baselines or just beyond the outfield fence.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Relief pitchers usually wait in the bullpen when they have yet to play in a game, rather than in the dugout with the rest of the team.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The starting pitcher also makes their final pregame warmups in the bullpen.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Managers can call coaches in the bullpen on an in-house telephone from the dugout to tell a certain pitcher to begin their warmup tosses.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] "Bullpen" is also used metonymically to describe a team's collection of relief pitchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] There are two on-deck circles in the field, one for each team, positioned in foul ground between home plate and the respective teams' benches.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The on-deck circle is where the next scheduled batter, or "on-deck" batter, warms up while waiting for the current batter to finish their turn.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The on-deck circle is either an area composed of bare dirt; a plain circle painted onto artificial turf; or often, especially at the professional level, a mat made from artificial material, with the team or league logo painted onto it.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The coach's boxes, located behind first and third base, are where the first and third base coaches are supposed to stand, although coaches often stand outside the box.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This is permissible as long as the coach does not interfere with play and the opposing team does not object (in which case the umpire shall ensure that all coaches on both teams must abide by the boundaries of the coach's boxes).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The coach's boxes are marked with chalk or paint.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In the early days of baseball, the term "coacher's box" was used, as "coach" was taken to be a verb.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] As the term "coach" evolved into a noun, the name of the box also changed.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The basic layout of the field has been little changed since the Knickerbocker Rules of the 1840s.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Those rules specified the distance from home to second as 42 "paces".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The dictionary definition of a "pace" at the time was 30 inches, yielding base paths of approximately 75 feet; however, if a "pace" of three feet was meant then the distance would have been 89 feet.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] It is not implausible that the early clubs simply stepped off the distance.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] 30 yards (90 feet) between the bases was first explicitly prescribed by the NABBP Convention of 1857.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Through trial and error, 90 feet had been settled upon as the optimal distance.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] 100 feet would have given too much advantage to the defense, and 80 feet too much to the offense.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The original Knickerbocker Rules did not specify the pitching distance explicitly; the 1854 Unified Rules stated "from Home to pitcher not less than fifteen paces".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] By the time major league baseball began in the 1870s, the pitcher was compelled to pitch from within a "box" whose front edge was 45 feet (14 m) from the "point" of home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Although they had to release the ball before crossing the line, as with bowlers in cricket, they also had to start their delivery from within the box, meaning that they could only run for a short distance before throwing; they could not run in from the field as bowlers do.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Furthermore, the pitcher had to throw underhand.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] By the 1880s, pitchers had mastered the underhand delivery—in fact, in 1880, there were two perfect games within a week of each other.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In an attempt to "increase the batting", the front edge of the pitcher's box was moved back 5 feet in 1881, to 50 feet (15 m) from home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The size of the box was altered over the following few years.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Pitchers were allowed to throw overhand starting in 1884, and that tilted the balance of power again.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In 1887, the box was set at 4 feet (1.2 m) wide and 5.5 feet (1.7 m) deep, with the front edge still 50 feet from the plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] However, the pitcher was compelled to deliver the ball with their back foot at the 55.5-foot (16.9 m) line of the box, thus somewhat restricting their ability to "power" the ball with their overhand delivery.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In 1893, the box was replaced by the pitcher's plate, although "the box" is still used today as a slang term for the pitcher's location on the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Exactly 5 feet was added to the point the pitcher had to toe, again "to increase the batting" (and hopefully to increase attendance, as fan interest had flagged somewhat), resulting in the seemingly peculiar pitching distance of 60.5 feet (18.44 m).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Some sources suggest that the pitching distance evolved from 45 to 50 to 60.5 feet.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] However, the first two were the "release point" and the third is the "pushoff point." The 1893 rule change added only 5 feet to the release point, not 10.5 feet.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Originally the pitcher threw from flat ground.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Gradually, the raised mound was developed, somewhat returning the advantage to the pitchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] From 1893 to 1950, a stipulation was added that the mound be no more than 15 inches above the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Before the mid-20th century, it was common for baseball fields to include a dirt pathway between the pitcher's mound and home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] This feature is sometimes known as the "keyhole" due to the shape that it makes together with the mound.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The keyhole was once as wide as the pitcher's box and resembled a cricket pitch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Sometimes this path extended through the batting area and all the way to the backstop.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Once the rounded pitcher's mound was developed, the path became more ornamental than practical, and was gradually thinned before being largely abandoned by the 1950s.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In recent years some ballparks, such as Comerica Park and Chase Field in the major leagues, have revived the feature for nostalgic reasons.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] From 1857 to 1867 home plate was a circular iron plate, painted or enameled white, covering "a space equal to one square foot of surface", i.e. with a diameter of ~13-1/2 inches.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In 1868 the plate was changed to a square, 12" on a side, originally set with the flat sides toward the pitcher and catcher; the new professional National Association rotated it 45 degrees in 1871.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In 1872 the rules required it to be made of white marble or stone set flush with the ground.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] For the rest of the century materials varied between stone, iron and wood, but at all times it was a white twelve-inch square.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The pentagonal shape and the mandatory use of rubber were developed by Robert Keating, who had pitched one game for the 1887 Baltimore Orioles; the new plate was adopted by the National League in 1900.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] From 1861 to 1874 the center, not the back, of the plate was situated on the intersection of the foul lines, and in 1875–76 was moved entirely into foul ground with the "pitcher's point" at the intersection.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] In 1877 it was moved forward to its modern location, wholly in fair territory.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] There were no batters' boxes before 1874.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Up until that time, the batter was required to hit with their front foot on a line passing through the center of the plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] The Sports Turf Managers Association (STMA) presents various awards each year.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] Starting in 2001, its Sports Turf Manager of the Year Awards have been presented annually in the Triple-A, Double-A, Class A, and Short-Season/Rookie divisions of Minor League Baseball and are chosen from the 16 league winners.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-field] STMA also presents the Baseball Field of the Year Award, which includes Schools and Parks, College/University and Professional categories.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus has originated several popular new statistical tools that have become hallmarks of baseball analysis.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus is accredited by the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Four of Baseball Prospectus's current regular writers are members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America and thus eligible to vote for nominees for Major League Baseball's post-season awards and the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus is formally an entity of Prospectus Entertainment Ventures, LLC, a private corporation that runs websites and publishes books focusing on the statistical analysis of the sports of baseball, basketball, and ice hockey.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] As of August 2014, the President & CEO is Joe Hamrahi, and Vice President is Dave Pease.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] For several years, Prospectus Entertainment Ventures (*PEV*) partnered with Football Outsiders for the publication and promotion of *Football Outsiders Almanac* (ISBN 1-4486-4845-9), before 2009 called *Pro Football Prospectus* (ISBN 0-452-28847-9).
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On October 10, 2007, PEV launched *Basketball Prospectus,* a new website for the analysis of men's college and pro basketball, with Joe Sheehan taking the role of Managing Editor and announcing the lineup of principal writer-analysts for the site.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Initially, this website did not require a subscription for access, but it introduced subscriptions in 2011 for access to most of the material on the site.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] *BasketballProspectus.com*'s first annual book, *College Basketball Prospectus 2008–2009* (ISBN 0-452-28987-4), was published in October 2008.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] It released *Pro Basketball Prospectus 2009–10* for purchase online in October 2009.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Subsequently, it published both *College Basketball Prospectus 2010–11* (ISBN 1-4538-7282-5) and *Pro Basketball Prospectus 2010–11* (ISBN 1-4538-6899-2) in both print and online (PDF) modes.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On March 19, 2008, Imagine Sports announced a strategic partnership with PEV and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Imagine sports owns the baseball simulation engine "Diamond Mind Baseball".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On October 14, 2008, PEV announced the acquisition of *Baseball Digest Daily* (BDD), an online blog devoted to baseball analysis and statistics.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Joe Hamrahi, new Chief Financial Officer of PEV and founder of BDD, reported that "PEV's decision to acquire Baseball Digest Daily further enhances the content offerings of Baseball Prospectus by adding some of the game's best analysts as well as over 100 pages of baseball news and original content.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In addition, BDD's player tracker provides a platform for serious fans and fantasy baseball enthusiasts to easily monitor the progress of their teams, allowing users to manipulate and track the progress of an unlimited set of players over a customized period of time".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On February 23, 2009, Prospectus Entertainment Ventures (PEV) launched the website *Puck Prospectus* with the intent of providing cutting-edge analysis of hockey.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Will Carroll assumed the role of the Executive Editor, and Andrew Rothstein, the founder of *Puck Prospectus*, assumed the role of the Managing Editor.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Puck Prospectus published its first annual book, *Puck Prospectus 2010–2011* (ISBN 1-4538-1784-0) in both online and print formats.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Initially a free site, *Puck Prospectus* introduced subscriptions in 2011.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On March 24, 2009, Baseball Prospectus announced that Nate Silver was stepping down as its Managing Partner, and Kevin Goldstein was assuming this role.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] At that time, PEV relinquished its previously announced financial interest in Silver's *FiveThirtyEight* blog.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] At the same time, it was announced that BP has a partnership relationship with ESPN.com.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In January 2010, PEV's Managing Partner Kevin Goldstein reported that one of BP's founding members, Joe Sheehan, had departed the organization.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] He reported that John Perrotto had been elevated to full-time status on the BP staff and would become the new Editor-in-Chief of *BaseballProspectus.com*, taking over that responsibility from Christina Kahrl.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] And he reported that Jeff Euston was joining the BP staff and that Euston's *Cot's Baseball Contracts* website would be joining the Baseball Prospectus family.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In February 2011, Perrotto was replaced as Editor-in-Chief by Steven Goldman.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In February 2010, BP's "Fantasy Manager" Marc Normandin announced that BP had established a partnership with *Heater Magazine.* *Heater Magazine* ceased publication after the 2010 season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In November 2011, Kevin Goldstein announced that he was stepping down as PEV's Managing Partner in favor of Joe Hamrahi.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On March 3, 2012, Hamrahi announced that Steven Goldman was stepping down as Editor-in-Chief of BaseballProspectus.com; Goldman had taken a position as a lead baseball writer for *Bleacher Report*.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Ben Lindbergh was named Managing Editor of Baseball Prospectus on March 5, 2012 and Editor-in-Chief of Baseball Prospectus on July 13, 2012.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On April 30, 2012, PEV's Managing Partner Joe Hamrahi announced that "Dan Brooks, Harry Pavlidis, and Brooks Baseball have agreed to team up and join forces with Baseball Prospectus.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] BrooksBaseball.net is the premier site for PITCHf/x analysis and pitch classification".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On March 15, 2013, after explaining a week earlier that its key staff of writers had been hired away by ESPN, Baseball Prospectus's Dave Pease declared in response to a question in the comments: "Basketball Prospectus will not be publishing any new content.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] On March 8, Pease had written: "You've probably noticed our Basketball Prospectus Premium coverage has been pretty quiet lately.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] You may have also noticed that our core pro writers, Kevin Pelton, Bradford Doolittle, and John Gasaway are now writing for ESPN Insider on a regular basis.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Late last year, we learned that, following their completion of the Pro Basketball Prospectus 2012–13 and College Basketball Prospectus 2012–13 annuals, Kevin, Bradford, and John would be moving to ESPN on a full-time basis".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus was founded in 1996 by Gary Huckabay, who recruited the initial contributor group of Clay Davenport, Rany Jazayerli, Christina Kahrl, and Joe Sheehan, with the publication of the first annual set of forecasts.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] "That first year, BP charged $20 for a statistics guide produced on a photocopier.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] It printed around 300 copies and sold about 170 to fellow statheads, even though the book was missing the St.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] 'It was terrible,' recalls Kahrl, 'but it nevertheless didn't discourage us.' Within a few years Brassey's Inc. published the guide, which grew to about 3,000 copies.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] The kind of sabermetric approach favored by Baseball Prospectus has gained significant acceptance by the management of many Major League Baseball clubs, notably the Boston Red Sox and Cleveland Indians.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] BP has often been considered the modern successor to Bill James' *Baseball Abstract* series of books in the 1980s.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Reflecting its legacy as a group of sabermetricians who met over the Internet, BP has no "main office." Working for BP is a second or part-time job for many of the regular staff, who conduct their work for BP in their own home offices.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] The website *BaseballProspectus.com* began in 1997 primarily as a way to present original sabermetric research; publish advanced baseball statistics such as EqA, the Davenport Translations (DT's), and VORP; and promote sales of the annual book.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Beginning in 2003, the site placed most of its new articles, its PECOTA forecasts, and some of its statistical databases in a "premium" section that could be accessed only by subscription.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] However, in May 2011, BP "announced it has made its entire archive of premium and fantasy content over one year old completely and permanently free to the public".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Until 2007, when the site began to post general advertising, the premium subscriptions and book sales were Baseball Prospectus' main source of revenues.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus does not publish a financial report or information about its subscriber base, but it appears to have used its income to expand its breadth of coverage, and it has not increased its subscription prices since initiating its premium service.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] It also offers a subscription to those interested in fantasy baseball, at a lower price than the premium subscriptions and giving access to fewer features and articles.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Given the competing career opportunities for some of BP's best-known and most statistics-savvy analysts, maintaining a fresh supply of sabermetrically sophisticated writers remains a challenge.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] At least three new regular BP writers (winner Ken Funck, Tim Kniker, and Matt Swartz) were discovered through this *Prospectus Idol* contest.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In addition, BP had added Eric Seidman to its staff early in 2009 and then acquired Russell Carleton ("Pizza Cutter") and Colin Wyers in December 2009 to bolster its coverage of technical sabermetric issues.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] As late as the Fall of 2008, Seidman, Swartz, Carleton, Wyers, Daniel Novick and BP Idol finalist Brian Cartwright made up the entire staff of "Statistically Speaking" aka StatSpeak at MVN.com.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Carleton left the BP staff in May 2010, but returned in July 2012.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Seidman and Swartz left in February 2011.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Wyers was hired away by the Houston Astros in October 2013.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In the press release announcing his hire, Jeff Luhnow noted, "Colin Wyers is a brilliant man with lots of well thought-out, practical, ideas.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] He is insuring the financial security of this company for years to come.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Oh yes, and his personal hygiene is above reproach".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] So teams court them as part of their effort to win games".
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] By the beginning of the 2011 baseball season, none of BP's founders was an active contributor to the website or publications, though some of their earlier articles were included in two *Best of Baseball Prospectus* compendia that were published in 2011.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers promote several theories on proper baseball management and analysis, many of which are contrary to those of conventional baseball wisdom.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus researchers have concluded that there is no repeatable ability of clutch hitting.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In an article published in 2006, Nate Silver argued that clutch hitting ability does exist to a degree.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] He argued that although not as important as traditional baseball analysis would suggest, clutch hitting ability was more significant than other sabermetric studies had shown.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] The article also found there to be a connection between clutch hitting ability and situational hitting, or the ability to adjust a hitting approach to fit the given situation.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers often successfully argue that traditional baseball statistics such as RBIs, wins, and batting average are poor reflections of a player's true contributions.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] For example, they have argued that RBIs are too dependent on factors outside of the player's control, namely the production of other hitters in the lineup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] They similarly argue that wins are too affected by factors such as the team's offense and bullpen.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers assert that teams are typically inefficient in their use of their best relievers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Teams typically assign their most effective reliever to the position of closer, using him in only save situations.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] According to many Baseball Prospectus writers, a team's best reliever should be used when the opposing team has its best chance at increasing its chances of winning.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Many writers argue that the sacrifice bunt and stolen base are overused in baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Teams will often attempt these plays when the score is close.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Writers for Baseball Prospectus often argue that teams are, on average, actually lowering their expected number of runs scored.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] They argue that stolen base attempts are not completed frequently enough for them to be beneficial to the offense.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] For sacrifice bunts, they argue that the team is giving up more by sacrificing an out than they gain by advancing a runner one base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Their thinking is derived from the grid of expected runs in an inning based on the outs and runner situation, which shows that the sacrifice is detrimental to a team given average players in most of the situations in which it is typically used.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In a series of articles in 2004, James Click argued that sacrifice bunts are beneficial in some situations, dependent on the quality of the batter at the plate and the situation in the game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers use a wide variety of sabermetric tools.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Voros McCracken's pathbreaking article on Defense Independent Pitching Statistics also first appeared on the BP website.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus, as well as other sabermetric analysts, are criticized for taking the human aspect out of the game of baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Nate Silver, BP's Managing Partner at the time, responded to this criticism in "An Open Letter to Murray Chass," including offering to meet Chass to watch a ballgame.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Silver expounded on the case for a positive impact of sabermetrics on the game of baseball in an article "How Sabermetrics Helps Build a Better Ballgame," published on *Baseball Analysts.com*.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Another type of criticism comes from those who believe that by broadening its coverage and audience, Baseball Prospectus is becoming more like the mainstream media and losing what made it unique.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus was widely criticized for publishing and aggressively promoting a 2003 story claiming that banished player/manager Pete Rose had reached an agreement to return to baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Will Carroll made the rounds on television and radio, claiming to have spoken to unnamed sources who had actually seen the agreement.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] Spokesmen for both Rose and Major League Baseball refuted the claim, but Carroll and his colleagues insisted their reporting was accurate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] No other news source confirmed the story.
[src:defensive-spectrum/baseball-prospectus] In fact, Rose was not reinstated and remains banned from baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 2006, *Time* named him in the *Time* 100 as one of the most influential people in the world.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 2003, James was hired as senior advisor on Baseball Operations for the Boston Red Sox and worked for the team for 17 years during which they won four World Series championships.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] He joined the United States Army in 1971.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] After his service, he graduated from the University of Kansas in 1973 with degrees in English and economics, and in 1975 with a degree in education.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] An aspiring writer and obsessive fan, James began writing baseball articles in his mid-twenties after leaving the United States Army.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Many of his first baseball writings came while he was doing night shifts as a security guard at the Stokely-Van Camp's pork and beans cannery.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Unlike most writers, his pieces did not recount games in epic terms or offer insights gleaned from interviews with players.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] A typical James piece posed a question (*e.g.,* "Which pitchers and catchers allow runners to steal the most bases?"), and then presented data and analysis that offered an answer.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Editors considered James's pieces so unusual that few believed them suitable for their readers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In an effort to reach a wider audience, James began self-publishing an annual book titled *The Bill James Baseball Abstract*, beginning in 1977.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Seventy-five people purchased the booklet.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The 1978 edition, subtitled *The 2nd annual edition of baseball's most informative and imaginative review*, sold 250 copies.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Beginning in 1979, James wrote an annual preview of the baseball season for *Esquire*, and continued to do so through 1984.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The first three editions of the *Baseball Abstract* garnered respect for James's work, including a very favorable review by Daniel Okrent in *Sports Illustrated*.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] New annual editions added essays on teams and players.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] By 1982 sales had increased tenfold, and a media conglomerate agreed to publish and distribute future editions.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] While writers had published books about baseball statistics before (most notably Earnshaw Cook's *Percentage Baseball*, in the 1960s), few had ever reached a mass audience.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Attempts to imitate James's work spawned a flood of books and articles that continues to this day.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 1988, James ceased writing the *Abstract*, citing workload-related burnout and concern about the volume of statistics on the market.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] He has continued to publish hardcover books about baseball history, which have sold well and received admiring reviews.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] These books include three editions of *The Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract* (1985, 1988, 2001, the last entitled *The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*).
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 2008, James launched Bill James Online.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Subscribers could read James's new, original writing and interact with one another—as well as with James—in a question-and-answer format.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The web site also offered new "profiles" of teams and players full of facts and statistics that hoped to map what James has termed "the lost island of baseball statistics".
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] On June 9, 2023, James wrote an article for the site announcing that it would soon be closed in order for James to "focus on other projects".
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In an essay published in the 1984 *Abstract*, James vented his frustration about Major League Baseball's refusal to publish play-by-play accounts of every game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James proposed the creation of Project Scoresheet, a network of fans that would work together to collect and distribute this information.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] While the resulting non-profit organization never functioned smoothly, it worked well enough to collect accounts of every game from 1984 through 1991.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James's publisher agreed to distribute two annuals of essays and data—the 1987 and 1988 editions of *Bill James Presents The Great American Baseball Statbook* (though only the first of these featured writing by James).
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The organization was eventually disbanded, but many of its members went on to form for-profit companies with similar goals and structure.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] STATS, Inc., the company James joined, provided data and analysis to every major media outlet before being acquired by Fox Sports in 2001.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Although James may be best known as an inventor of statistical tools, he has often written on the limitations of statistics and urged humility concerning their place amid other kinds of information about baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] To James, context is paramount: he was among the first to emphasize the importance of adjusting traditional statistics for park factors and to stress the role of luck in a pitcher's win–loss record.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Many of his statistical innovations are arguably less important than the underlying ideas.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] When he introduced the notion of secondary average, it was as a vehicle for the then-counterintuitive concept that batting average represents only a fraction of a player's offensive contribution.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] (The runs-created statistic plays a similar role vis-à-vis the traditional RBI.) Some of his contributions to the language of baseball, like the idea of the "defensive spectrum", border on being entirely non-statistical.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Oakland Athletics general manager Billy Beane began applying sabermetric principles to running his low-budget team in the early 2000s, to notable effect, as chronicled in Michael Lewis' book *Moneyball*.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 2003, James was hired by a former reader, John Henry, the new owner of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] One point of controversy was in handling the relief pitching of the Red Sox.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James had previously published analysis of the use of the closer in baseball, and had concluded that the traditional use of the closer both overrated the abilities of that individual and used him in suboptimal circumstances.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] He wrote that it is "far better to use your relief ace when the score is tied, even if that is the seventh inning, than in the ninth inning with a lead of two or more runs." The Red Sox in 2003 staffed their bullpen with several marginally talented relievers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Red Sox manager Grady Little was never fully comfortable with the setup, and designated unofficial closers and reshuffled roles after a bad outing.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] When Boston lost a number of games due to bullpen failures, Little reverted to a traditional closer approach and moved Byung-hyun Kim from being a starting pitcher to a closer.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The Red Sox did not follow James's idea of a bullpen with no closer, but with consistent overall talent that would allow the responsibilities to be shared.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Red Sox reliever Alan Embree thought the plan could have worked if the bullpen had not suffered injuries.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] During the 2004 regular season Keith Foulke was used primarily as a closer in the conventional model; however, Foulke's usage in the 2004 postseason was along the lines of a relief ace with multiple inning appearances at pivotal times of the game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Houston Astros manager Phil Garner also employed a relief ace model with his use of Brad Lidge in the 2004 postseason.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] During his tenure with the Red Sox, James published several new sabermetric books (see #Bibliography below).
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] After the Red Sox suffered through a disastrous 2012 season, Henry stated that James had fallen "out of favor [in the front office] over the last few years for reasons I really don't understand.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] On October 24, 2019, James announced his retirement from the Red Sox, saying that he had "fallen out of step with the organization" and added that he hadn't earned his paycheck with the Red Sox for the last couple of years.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] During his time with the team, Bill James received four World Series rings for the team's 2004, 2007, 2013, and 2018 World Series titles.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James has written two true crime books, *Popular Crime: Reflections on the Celebration of Violence* (2011) and – together with his daughter Rachel McCarthy James – *The Man from the Train* (2017).
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The latter is an attempt to link scores of murders of entire families in the early 20th century United States to a single perpetrator.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Those murders include the Villisca axe murders.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The Jameses propose a solution to the murders based on the signature elements these killings share with each other.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James is a fan of the University of Kansas men's basketball team and has written about basketball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] He has created a formula for what he calls a "safe lead" in the sport.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Michael Lewis, in his 2003 book *Moneyball*, dedicates a chapter to James's career and sabermetrics as background for his portrayal of Billy Beane and the Oakland Athletics' unlikely success.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James was inducted into the Baseball Reliquary's Shrine of the Eternals in 2007.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James was profiled on *60 Minutes* on March 30, 2008, in his role as a sabermetric pioneer and Red Sox advisor.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 2010, he was inducted into the Irish American Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James made a guest appearance on *The Simpsons* 2010 episode "MoneyBART".
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Steven Soderbergh's planned film adaptation of *Moneyball* would have featured an animated version of James as a "host".
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] This script was discarded when director Bennett Miller and writer Aaron Sorkin succeeded Soderbergh on the project.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Ultimately, the 2011 film mentions James several times.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] His bio is briefly recapped, and Billy Beane is depicted telling John Henry that Henry's hiring of James is the reason Beane is interested in the Red Sox general manager job.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In his *Baseball Book 1990*, James heavily criticized the methodology of the Dowd Report, which was an investigation (commissioned by baseball commissioner Bart Giamatti) on the gambling activities of Pete Rose.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James reproached commissioner Giamatti and his successor, Fay Vincent, for their acceptance of the Dowd Report as the final word on Rose's gambling.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James expanded his defense of Rose in his 2001 book *The New Historical Baseball Abstract*, with a detailed explanation of why he found the case against Rose flimsy.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James wrote "I would characterize the evidence that Rose bet on baseball as... well, not quite non-existent.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] It is extremely weak." This countered the popular opinion that the case against Rose was a slam dunk, and several critics claimed James misstated some of the evidence in his defense of Rose.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In 2004, Rose admitted publicly he had bet on baseball and confirmed the Dowd Report was correct.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James remained steadfast, continuing to insist that the evidence available to Dowd at the time was insufficient to reach the conclusion that it did.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] On November 4, 2011, Jerry Sandusky was indicted for committing sex crimes against young boys, which brought the Penn State child sex abuse scandal to national attention.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] On July 12, 2012, the Freeh report was released, charging Paterno and three other University officials with covering up reports of sexual assaults and enabling the attacker to prey on other children for more than a decade, often in Pennsylvania State University facilities.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Soon afterwards, during an interview on ESPN radio, James claimed that the Freeh report's characterizations of Paterno as a powerful figure were wrong, and that it was not Paterno's responsibility to report allegations of child molestation to the police.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] He was isolated and he was not nearly as powerful as people imagine him to have been." When asked if he knew anyone who had showered with a boy they were not related to, James said it was a common practice when he was growing up.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] "That was actually quite common in the town I grew up in.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] The July 2012 interview comments were widely criticized.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] James's employer, the Boston Red Sox, issued a statement disavowing the comments James made and saying that he had been asked not to make further public comments on the matter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] On November 7, 2018, James participated in a Twitter conversation regarding comments made by agent Scott Boras about teams "tanking".
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] This was arguably consistent with thoughts James had publicly expressed prior to his affiliation with the Red Sox.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Nonetheless, in the context of James's association with the Red Sox front office and baseball's checkered labor history (including alleged collusion amongst the owners in the previous offseason to curb free agent salaries), the tweets were taken by many as inflammatory.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Major League Baseball Players Association executive director Tony Clark called James's comments "reckless and insulting".
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] Other active or former players also objected.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bill-james] In January 2024, James announced that he had suffered a stroke, which impeded the use of his right hand.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A **bunt** is a batting technique in baseball or fastpitch softball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Official Baseball Rules define a *bunt* as follows: "A bunt is a batted ball not swung at, but intentionally met with the bat and tapped slowly within the infield." To bunt, the batter loosely holds the bat in front of home plate and intentionally taps the ball into play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A properly executed bunt will create weak contact with the ball or strategically direct it, forcing the infielders to make a difficult defensive play to record an out.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The strategy in bunting is to ground the ball into fair territory, as far from the fielders as possible but within the infield.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] This requires not only physical dexterity and concentration, but also an awareness of the fielders' positions in relation to the baserunner or baserunners, their likely reactions to the bunt, and knowledge of the pitcher's most likely pitches.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The bunt is typically executed by the batter turning his body toward the pitcher and sliding one hand up the barrel of the bat to help steady it.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Depending on the situation, the batter might square up either before the pitcher winds up, or as the pitched ball approaches the plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Sometimes, a batter may square up, then quickly retract the bat and take a full swing as the pitch is delivered.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] In a sacrifice bunt, the batter will put the ball into play with the intention of advancing a baserunner, in exchange for the batter being thrown out.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The sacrifice bunt is most often used to advance a runner from first to second base, though the runner may also be advanced from second to third base, or from third to home.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The sacrifice bunt is most often used in close, low-scoring games, and it is usually performed by weaker hitters.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A sacrifice bunt is not counted as an at-bat.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] In general, when sacrifice bunting, a batter will square to bunt well before the pitcher releases the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The squeeze play occurs when the batter sacrifices with the purpose of scoring a runner from third base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] In the *suicide squeeze*, in which the runner on third base starts running for home plate as soon as the pitcher starts to pitch the ball, it is integral that the batter bunt the ball successfully, or the runner will likely be tagged out easily.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Due to the high-risk nature of this play, it is not often executed, but can often be an exciting moment within the game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Alternatively, in the lower-risk *safety squeeze*, the runner on third waits for the ball to be bunted before breaking for home.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] If a runner scores in a squeeze play, the batter may be credited with an RBI.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A batter may also *bunt for a base hit*.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] This is not a sacrifice play, because the batter is trying to reach base safely, without any intention of advancing a runner.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A batter may try to bunt for a base hit while there are runners on base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] In this case, if the runner advances and the batter is thrown out, and if the official scorer judges that the intention of the batter was to bunt for a base hit, then the batter will not receive credit for a sacrifice bunt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A batter bunting for a base hit will often hold back his bunt while the pitcher begins delivering the ball, in order to surprise the fielders.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] If successful, the bunt is scored as a hit single.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Rarely does a bunt result in a double, and never has one resulted in a triple in MLB.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Often when attempting to bunt for a base hit, the batter will begin running as he is bunting the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Left-handed batters perform this more often than right-handed hitters, because their stance in the batter's box is closer to first base, and they do not need to run across home plate, where the ball will be pitched, as they bunt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The action of squaring to bunt is compromised during a drag bunt, as the feet are not set.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Players sometimes get one hand up the barrel, and other times bunt with both hands at the base of the bat.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] There have been instances of one-handed drag bunts as well; Rafael Furcal has been known to try such a bunt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A *swinging bunt* occurs when a poorly hit ball rolls a short distance into play, much like a bunt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A swinging bunt is often the result of a checked swing, and only has the appearance of a bunt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] It is not a true bunt, and if the scorer judges that the batter intended to hit the ball, it cannot be counted as a sacrifice.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] There is also a "slug" bunt that is intended to surprise the opposing defense, as the desired effect is a hard-hit ball into the infield defense that is expecting a standard bunt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Fielding a bunt can be more difficult than fielding a normally batted ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Bunted balls are typically slow, so fielders must *charge* the ball to get to it quickly, in order to throw out a runner in time.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Well-placed bunts can sometimes be impossible to field, and result in base hits.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The tactic in bunting for a base hit is to hit the ball fast enough to get it past the pitcher, but slow enough to not allow time for the other infielders to make a play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] It is not unusual for all three fielders to try to field the ball, and for nobody to cover the bag, or for no one to try to field the ball, assuming someone else will handle it.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Teams use a *rotation play* to defend against the bunt: the first baseman will charge the bunt and the second baseman "rotates" out of his usual position to cover first base and receive the throw.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The shortstop covers the base towards which the runner is headed.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] A foul bunt that is not caught in flight is always counted as a strike, even if it is a third strike and thus results in a strikeout of the batter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] This is distinct from all other foul balls which, if not caught in flight, are only counted as a strike if *not* a third strike.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] This special exception applies only to true bunts, not on any bunt-like contacts that might occur during a full swing or check-swing.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] If a batter bunts the ball and his bat hits the ball again after initial contact, it is a dead ball even if by accident.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Additionally, the infield fly rule is not applied to bunts popped-up in the air.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Instead, the intentional drop rule (Rule 6.05k) that also applies to line drives can be invoked.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] It is not known when the bunt was introduced; the earliest known reference to a bunt-like hit appears in the account of a game played in 1864 between the junior squads ("muffins") of the Brooklyn Excelsior and Enterprise clubs: "The feature of the play was the batting of Prof.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Bassler of the Enterprise team...Being an original of the first water, he adopted an original theory in reference to batting, which we are obliged to confess is not of the most striking character.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] For much of his career, Pearce used his 'tricky hit' to tremendous effect as the rules permitted it to roll foul and still be counted as a hit.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The bunt was not common until the 1880s, and was not an accepted part of baseball strategy until the 20th century.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] The bunt has enjoyed periodic waves of popularity throughout baseball history, coinciding with the periodic shifts of dominance between pitching and hitting over the decades.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] During periods of pitching dominance, for example, during the dead-ball era or the 1960s, bunting was an important offensive weapon.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Conversely, during periods of hitting dominance, for example, the 1990s and 2000s, the value of the bunt has often been questioned.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Teams following the "Moneyball" school of baseball thought (such as the Oakland Athletics, the Boston Red Sox, and the 2004–2005 Los Angeles Dodgers) have shown a tendency to shun the sacrifice bunt almost entirely.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] However, a canvass of the 2002–2005 World Series champions (the 2002 Los Angeles Angels being the "small ball" trendsetter for the 2000s) reveals that each team used bunting frequently in order to overcome power hitting teams.
[src:defensive-spectrum/bunt-baseball] Nevertheless, the role of the bunt in baseball strategy is one of the perennial topics of discussion for baseball fans.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Positioned behind home plate and facing toward the outfield, the catcher can see the whole field and is therefore in the best position to direct and lead the other players in a defensive play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher typically calls for pitches using PitchCom, or hand signals.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The calls are based on the pitcher's mechanics and strengths, as well as the batter's tendencies and weaknesses.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Essentially, the catcher controls what happens during the game when the ball is not "in play".
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Foul tips, bouncing balls in the dirt and contact with runners during plays at the plate are all events to be handled by the catcher, necessitating the use of protective equipment.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] This includes a mask, chest and throat protectors, shin guards, and a heavily padded catcher's mitt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Though rare, some chest protectors may extend lower to provide some shield to the genitalia; wearing a pelvic protector or cup, depending on the case, is preferred and more common.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The physical and mental demands of being involved in every defensive play can wear catchers down over a long season, and can have a negative effect on their offensive output.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Because of the strategic defensive importance of catching, if a catcher has exceptional defensive skills, teams are often willing to overlook their relative offensive weaknesses.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] A knowledgeable catcher's ability to work with the pitcher, via pitch selection and location, can diminish the effectiveness of the opposing team's offense.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Many great defensive catchers toiled in relative anonymity, because they did not produce large offensive numbers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Notable examples of light-hitting, defensive specialists were Jerry Grote, Jeff Mathis, Martín Maldonado, Ray Schalk, Jim Hegan, Jim Sundberg and Brad Ausmus.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Schalk's career batting average of .253 is the lowest of any position player in the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] His selection for enshrinement in 1955 was largely a tribute to his outstanding defensive skills.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In the numbering system used to record baseball plays, the catcher is assigned the number '2'.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In the middle of the nineteenth century, the game of baseball began to evolve from a sport played by amateurs for recreation into a more serious game played by professionals.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] One of the most dramatic changes was the transition of the pitcher's delivery from an underhand motion to an overhanded throw.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Before the American Civil War, the pitcher's role was to initiate the action by offering an underhanded throw to the batter, in much the same way that a basketball referee offers up a jump ball to begin play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Since this type of pitching often caused the batter to hit lazy, foul pop-ups, catchers played their position approximately twenty to twenty-five feet behind the batter, and wore no protective equipment.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] As the game progressed towards professionals and became more serious, pitchers began to attempt to prevent the batter from hitting the ball by throwing faster pitches.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] With the introduction of the called strike in 1858, catchers began inching closer to home plate due to the rules requirement that a strikeout could only be completed by a catch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The rules governing the delivery of pitches proved to be hard to enforce, and pitchers continued to stretch the boundaries of the rules until the 1870s when the release point of pitches had reached the pitcher's waist level.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Pitchers had begun throwing overhand by 1884, when the National League made a rule change removing all restrictions on the pitcher's delivery.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] These developments meant that catchers began to take on a crucial defensive role, as a pitcher's deceptive deliveries could only be effective if the catcher was capable of fielding them.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The progression of the catcher positioning themselves closer to the plate would lead to changes in pitching deliveries that would revolutionize the sport.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In the 1870s, pitcher Candy Cummings was able to introduce the curveball because his catcher, Nat Hicks, fielded his position in close proximity to home plate and was able to catch the deceptive pitch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Other specialized pitches such as the spitball and the knuckleball followed, which further emphasized the defensive importance of the catcher's position.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] At about the same time that catchers began fielding their position closer to home plate, baseball teams began using a less rubbery ball which led to a decline in the number of runs scored.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In the 1860s it was common for teams to score fifty or sixty runs in a game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The combination of the new, harder ball and the continuation of the rise in pitcher's release points helped usher in what became known as the Dead-ball era.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The decrease in run production placed greater significance on stolen bases and bunts, which in turn emphasized the crucial defensive role played by catchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In 1901, the National League introduced a new rule specifying that the catcher must stand within 10 feet of home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The American League adopted the rule the following year.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The rising velocity of pitches in conjunction with catchers gradually moving closer to home plate significantly increased the risk of injuries for catchers, especially face and hand injuries.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] By the late 1870s, catchers began to use padded, fingerless gloves to protect their hands, and in 1877 the first protective catcher's mask was used.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The first catchers to use protective masks sometimes had their courage called into question, but the effectiveness of the masks in preventing injuries meant that they became widely accepted.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In the 1880s, the first padded chest protectors came into use, and in 1888 specialized catcher's mitts used on the non-throwing hand began to be used.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Schenck of Princeton University was the first to use chest protectors when he stuffed copies of The Daily Princetonian under his shirt during a game against Harvard University.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] A Boston sporting goods company noticed his innovation and began producing the wearable chest pads.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The final pieces of protective gear were shin guards which were first worn by catcher Roger Bresnahan in 1907.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Together, the rules changes and the new protective equipment transformed the catcher's defensive role to the way that it is presently played.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher is usually the first to notice the tendencies, quirks, and peculiarities of each home-plate umpire.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Some umpires favor high strikes, pitched balls that are technically above the strike zone but appear, to the umpire, to be good.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Conversely, some umpires will call low pitches strikes even when they are slightly below the knees.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Other umpires have an inside bias or an outside bias; some umpires have more than one bias; some are uniformly lenient; some have very restricted notions of the strike zone, and the pitcher will constantly feel that their pitches are unfairly judged.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher can exploit an umpire's tendencies by taking them into account in when receiving the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher can help their pitcher get more strike calls from the umpire by using a technique called "framing".
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] This practice is a matter of a catcher keeping the mitt inside the strike zone, or making the pitch appear as close to the strike zone, when receiving the pitch, thereby giving the plate umpire the impression that the pitch is in the strike zone, even if it is not.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] When framing, a catcher will also hold their mitt still for a second or two so that the umpire has an opportunity to thoroughly consider their call (and, hopefully, let their innate biases influence their decision in a direction favorable to the catcher's team).
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher, when receiving a borderline pitch, usually has several options in how they make the catch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] They can catch the pitch in the webbing of their mitt or in the heel; they can catch the pitch on their forehand or backhand, as necessary; they can catch a low pitch with the mitt pointed upward or downward.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] These choices help the catcher to create a favorable presentation (or frame) for the umpire.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] A variation on "framing" is called "pulling pitches".
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The general approach is to catch the half of the ball that is outside the strike zone and show the umpire only the half of the ball, lodged in the mitt, that is closer to the zone.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The illusion is often enhanced with a slight 'tug' of the mitt (of an inch or two) toward the strike zone.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] By rule, the catcher must station directly back of the plate (generally in the catcher's box) the moment a pitch is thrown but may leave at any time to catch a pitch or make a play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The moment an intentional ball leaves a pitcher's hand, the catcher must have both feet in the catcher's box.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher is the only defensive player who is allowed to be in foul territory when a pitch is thrown.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] A catcher's balk occurs when the catcher is not properly set in the designated box.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Once the pitcher releases the ball and the catcher is caught outside of this zone, the play is thrown out.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The term "catcher's balk" is not official, but it is common to hear among catchers and umpires alike.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] If a pitch is thrown and the catcher has extended their arm resulting in the catcher's glove being contacted by the batter's swinging bat, a catcher's interference is called, and the batter is awarded first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] If the bases were loaded, it results in a run being scored, but since it is an error, the batter is not credited with a run batted in.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher's interference call is uncommon.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Also, an interference penalty may be declined by the batting team, such as when a better result ensues.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] To block balls that a pitcher throws on a bounce toward home plate (pitches that are said to be "in the dirt"), the catcher will slide their body to the left or right, as necessary, to place themselves directly in the path of the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Once in position, they push towards the ball while dropping to their knees, place their mitt between their legs to prevent the ball from passing through, and lean forward to deaden the rebound when, and if, the ball bounces off their thigh or torso.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Although inexperienced catchers may try to catch the errant pitch with the mitt, coaches often prioritize the catcher's ability to "keep the ball in front of the body" than to make a catch with their mitt.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Ideally, the catcher will be able to knock the ball to the ground where it will stop within arm's reach.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] To perform this properly, without the ball being deflected in an undesirable direction, the catcher must angle their body so that their chest is always leaning forward, toward home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Tucking your chin or looking the ball in will help with deadening the ball like this.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] This maneuver is often difficult, and its difficulty depends largely on how fast the ball is traveling, the angle at which the ball is thrown into the ground, where it first hits the ground, the firmness of the ground it hits, and the manner in which it is spinning.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] As of April 2011 15 of 30 Major League Baseball managers were former catchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Because catchers are considered a captain on the field (and some, such as Thurman Munson and Jason Varitek were in fact team captains), they are often in charge of planning defensive plays; thus, the catcher will give signs to the pitcher for what pitch is to be thrown.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Calling the game refers to the act of catchers deciding the type of pitch delivered to home plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The responsibility for selecting the type of pitch was traditionally made by the catcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] It is not unusual for a catcher to briefly look at the posture and position of the batter-in-turn prior to calling the next pitch; even the way a batter holds the bat may shed some indication of what the strategy may be.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The selection of which pitch to use can depend on a wide variety of situations such as the type of hitter that is being faced, whether there are any base runners, how many outs have been made in the inning, or the current score, among others.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Since a catcher uses their fingers to signal and communicate with the pitcher, they may wear colorful stickers on their nails to accentuate the motion of the fingers and thus help with the visibility of the signal.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] As an alternative, the catcher may wear painted nails, such as with fluorescent polish.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Starting in 2022, Major League catchers began wearing a PitchCom device on their wrist.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] This was done in an attempt to curb the prevalence of sign stealing, which reached its peak after the Houston Astros were caught stealing signs during their World Series-winning 2017 season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In addition, a lefty's throw would tend to come in on the shortstop side of the bag, while a righty's throw would be on the second base side of the bag, which is where the runner is coming in.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Consequently, players who are left-handed rarely play catcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Left-handed catchers have only caught eleven big-league games since 1902, and Jack Clements, who played for 17 years at the end of the nineteenth century, is the only man in the history of baseball to play more than three hundred games as a left-handed catcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] However, some observers, including the famed statistician Bill James and ESPN writer Rob Neyer, have suggested that the real reason that there are no left-handed catchers is because left-handed players with strong throwing arms are almost always encouraged, at an early age, to become pitchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Benny Distefano, the last lefty thrower to catch a big-league game (in 1989), noted that lefty catchers have difficulty on bunts up the third base line and on fielding throws home for plays at the plate.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Others suggest that fielding bunts up the 3rd base line would give the catcher a better throw to 1st base or 2nd base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Unlike the other fielders, the catcher and pitcher must start every play in a designated area.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher must be behind home plate in the catcher's box, while the pitcher must be on the pitcher's mound, with one foot in contact with the pitcher's rubber.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Once the ball is in play, however, the catcher and pitcher, like the other fielders, can respond to any part of the field necessary to make or assist in a defensive play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In certain game situations, typically a ball batted to the shortstop or third baseman with no runners on base, **the catcher may be expected to back-up first base in case the first baseman misses or mishandles a throw**.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Any failure by the catcher can have dire consequences for their team.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Passed balls are possible whenever one or more runners are on base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] A failure to catch a ball thrown from the outfield on a play at home plate, or a failure to tag a runner, means that the defensive team fails to record an all-important out and, instead, it allows a run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] On an attempt to prevent a stolen base, a catcher's bad throw might careen past the infielder and skip into the outfield, allowing an additional advance by the baserunner.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Though not exactly a play, **"psyching the batter"** refers to a casual attempt by the catcher to distract the batter prior to the pitcher throwing the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] As long as it does not fall in a lack of sportsmanship, such as offensiveness, and as long as the umpire permits it, the catcher may mention a specific throw or say something funny to try to distract the opponent to cause them to err.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Because of the close mental relationship and trust that a successful pitcher must have with his catcher, a number of catchers throughout history have become preferred by pitchers, to the point that the catcher will almost always (especially during the regular season) start along with the pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher is then informally referred to as that pitcher's *personal catcher*.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Naturally, the potential problem with this arrangement is that if the pitcher prefers to work with the team's backup catcher, then the regular catcher—presumably the better player—must be benched.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] However, because of the physically grueling nature of the position, many "regular" catchers are asked to either rest relatively frequently or play a different position such as first base or designated hitter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Personal catchers are often used for pitchers who specialize in throwing knuckleballs because of the difficulty of catching such an inconsistent and erratic pitch.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher is the most physically demanding position in baseball, more so than the pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Despite being heavily padded, catchers routinely suffer some of the worst physical abuse in baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher has the physically risky job of blocking the plate to prevent base runners from reaching home and scoring runs.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Catchers also constantly get bruised and battered by pitches, foul balls, and occasionally the bat in an undisciplined follow-through of the batter's swing.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Catchers also are prone to knee ailments stemming from the awkward crouching stance they assume.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Prominent examples of catchers switching position (mainly first base) in mid-career include Mike Napoli, Craig Biggio, B.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Surhoff, Joe Torre, Víctor Martínez, Joe Mauer, Carlos Santana, Brandon Inge, and Dale Murphy (although Murphy was also known as a poor thrower to the pitcher and to second base, nearly hitting pitchers in the process).
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] As a result, catchers often have shorter careers than players at other positions; consequently, few catchers hold batting records that require many seasons of play to compile.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Mike Piazza is the only catcher in history with more than 400 career home runs, and no catcher has amassed 3,000 career hits (Iván Rodríguez leads all Major League catchers with 2,844 hits).
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Although 3,000 hit club member Craig Biggio played his first three full seasons as a catcher, he played his remaining sixteen seasons at second base and in the outfield.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The larger or heavier the catcher, the greater the health risks associated with repeatedly assuming a crouching or squatting position; knees and backs are especially vulnerable to "wear-and-tear" injuries.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Catchers also have an increased risk of circulatory abnormalities in the catching hand.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] A study of minor-league ballplayers showed that, of 36 players in various positions, all nine of the catchers had hand pain during a game, and several had chronic pain in the catching hand.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Catching high-speed pitches can, in some cases, cause the index finger on the gloved hand to swell to twice the size of the other fingers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Ultrasound and blood-pressure tests showed altered blood flow in the gloved hand of five of the catchers, a far higher incidence than in the hands of players at other baseball positions.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] In addition to their protective equipment, a catcher usually also adopts practices that minimize the risk of injury.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] For instance, unlike fielders elsewhere on the field, a catcher tries, to the extent possible, to catch the ball with their gloved hand alone.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] An outfielder may catch a fly ball by covering the ball, once it strikes the pocket of their glove, with their bare hand in order to secure it.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] The catcher, however, tries to keep their bare hand, which is highly vulnerable to injury, out of harm's way by presenting the pitcher with a target (the large round glove) while hiding their unprotected throwing hand behind their back or ankle.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] By doing so, the bare hand cannot be struck by a foul tip.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Many broken fingers, split fingernails, and grotesque dislocations are avoided by adherence to this simple expedient.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Given the physical punishment suffered by catchers, the pieces of equipment associated with the position are often referred to as "the tools of ignorance".
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] This is an ironic expression; the catcher typically has the most thorough understanding of baseball tactics and strategies of any player on a team.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Catchers often experience knee tendinitis because of the constant squatting and bending of the knees while catching.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] As of 2024, twenty men who played primarily as catchers have been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, in Cooperstown, New York.
[src:defensive-spectrum/catcher] Catchers are also represented in a number of other Baseball Halls of Fame around the world, such as in the Canadian Baseball Hall of Fame or the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] A **center fielder**, abbreviated **CF**, is the outfielder in baseball who plays defense in **center field** – the baseball and softball fielding position between left field and right field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] In the numbering system used to record defensive plays, the center fielder is assigned the number 8.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] Outfielders must cover large distances, so speed, instincts and quickness to react to the ball are key.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] They must be able to catch fly balls above their heads and on the run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] They must be able to throw the ball accurately over a long distance to be effective.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] As well as the requirements above, the center fielder must be the outfielder who has the best combination of speed and throwing distance.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] The center fielder "covers more 'grass' than any other player" (see photo) and, most likely, will catch the most fly balls.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] The position also has the greatest responsibility among the three outfielders for coordinating their play to prevent collisions when converging on a fly ball, and on plays where the center fielder does not make the catch, he must position himself behind the corner outfielder as backup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] The center outfielder is the captain of the outfield and has the authority to call off the corner fielders when he has a better chance to catch the ball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] Aside from requiring more speed and range, the center field position is slightly easier to field because balls tend to fly on a straight path, rather than curving as they do for the other outfield positions.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] A center fielder's vision and depth perception is a coveted skill and must be above average.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] Because the position requires a good arm and fast legs, center field is generally where the team puts its best all-around athletes; as a result, center fielders are often fine hitters as well.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] Many center fielders are renowned as excellent batters and base runners.
[src:defensive-spectrum/center-fielder] When a base runner is trying to steal second base the center fielder must back up second base on throws from the catcher to second base in case the second baseman misses the catch or it is a bad throw.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] In sabermetrics, the **defensive spectrum** is a graphical representation of the positions on a baseball field, arranged from the easiest (such as first base and the outfield corners) on the left to the hardest (such as the catcher and middle infielders) on the right.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] In some versions of the defensive spectrum, pitcher and catcher are not included, since the demands of those positions are so specialized as to be inapplicable to players at other positions.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] The designated hitter is sometimes omitted as well, since that player does not take part in defensive plays.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] As an example of the concept in action, players who are drafted by Major League Baseball teams as shortstops are far more likely to ultimately end up at a different position than players who are drafted as first basemen.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Like many original sabermetric concepts, the idea of a defensive spectrum was first introduced by Bill James in his *Baseball Abstract* series of books during the 1980s.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] The basic premise of the spectrum is that positions on the right side of the spectrum are more difficult than the positions on the left side.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Therefore, the positions are easier to fill as one goes left on the spectrum, since the physical demands are less.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] A corollary to this is that, since defensive skill is at less of a premium on the left side, players at those positions must provide more offense than those on the right.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Another corollary is that players can generally move from right to left along the spectrum successfully during their careers (especially as they age), but moving a player from left to right is quite risky.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] A retrospective analysis of the 140-year history of baseball shows that the defensive spectrum shifted once.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] In the late 19th century and early 20th century, third base was generally considered to be more challenging than second base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] This was because the double play was relatively uncommon in this period; thus, the third baseman, who had to field hard hit grounders and throw the ball 120 feet to first base, had a far more challenging job than the second baseman, who threw the ball 70 feet at most.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Frequent bunting also meant that the third baseman would be challenged defensively more often.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] However, by the 1920s and 1930s, the defensive spectrum began to shift.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Double plays were steadily becoming more common, increasing the defensive responsibilities of the second baseman.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Offense correspondingly became more important at third base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] One of the new breed of third basemen was Harlond Clift of the St.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Louis Browns, who became the first third baseman to hit 30 home runs.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] By 1945, second base was firmly established as a more important position defensively than third base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] In the early 2020s, due in part to increasing numbers of strikeouts and use of infield shifts, teams have become increasingly willing to move players to more difficult positions (rightward along the spectrum).
[src:defensive-spectrum/defensive-spectrum] Players such as Ryan McMahon, Max Muncy, Travis Shaw, and Mike Moustakas have transitioned, either permanently or temporarily, from third base to second base as part of a trend of physically larger athletes being placed at the latter position.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The **designated hitter** (**DH**) is a baseball player who bats in place of the pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Unlike other players in a team's lineup, they generally only play as an offensive player and usually do not play defense as a fielder or a pitcher during a game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Due to their specialized offensive-only role, the designated hitter is generally expected to produce above average offensive stats and production compared to other players who play defense.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In Major League Baseball, the position is authorized by Rule 5.11 of the Official Baseball Rules.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] It was adopted by the American League in 1973 and by the National League in 2022, making it universal in MLB.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Within that time frame, nearly all amateur, collegiate, and professional leagues worldwide adopted the designated hitter or some variant, a major exception being Nippon Professional Baseball's Central League, which plans to adopt it in 2027.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The designated hitter is a player who does not play a position in the field, but instead replaces the pitcher in the batting order.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, a starting pitcher (but not relievers) may choose to also start as the designated hitter so that the pitcher bats for himself.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The DH may only be used for the pitcher (and not any other position player) as stated in Rule 5.11.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Use of the DH is optional, but must be determined before the start of the game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If a team does not begin a game with a DH, the team's pitchers (or pinch hitters) must bat for the entire game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The designated hitter can be moved to a fielding position during the game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If the DH is moved to another position, his team forfeits the role of designated hitter, and the pitcher or another player (the latter possible only in case of a multiple substitution) would bat in the spot of the position player replaced by the former DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If the designated hitter is moved to pitcher, any subsequent pitcher (or pinch-hitter thereof) would bat should that spot in the batting order come up again (except for a further multiple substitution).
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Likewise, if a pinch-hitter bats for a non-pitcher, and then remains in the game as the pitcher, the team would forfeit the use of the DH for the remainder of the game, and the player who was DH would become a position player (or exit the game).
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If that player starts the game as a designated hitter and pitches out of the bullpen, the team would lose the designated hitter once his relief appearance is over, unless he is moved to another position on the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The exception was added by MLB for the 2022 season, coincident with the introduction of the universal DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The rule change was subsequently applied for international-level games, starting with the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Unlike other positions, the DH is "locked" into the batting order.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] No multiple substitution may be made to alter the batting rotation of the DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In other words, a double switch involving the DH and a position player (with the exception of players started as starting pitcher and designated hitter) is not legal.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] For example, if the DH is batting fourth and the catcher is batting eighth, the manager cannot replace both players so as to have the new catcher bat fourth and the new DH bat eighth.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Once a team loses its DH under any of the scenarios already discussed, the double switch becomes fully available, and may well be used via necessity, should the former DH be replaced in the lineup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In Major League Baseball, during interleague play between 1997 and 2021, the DH rule was applied to a game based on the rules of the home team's league.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If the game was played in an American League park, the designated hitter could be used; in a National League park, the pitcher must bat or else be replaced with a pinch-hitter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] On June 12, 1997, San Francisco Giants outfielder Glenallen Hill became the first National League DH in a regular-season game, when the Giants met the American League Texas Rangers at The Ballpark in Arlington in interleague play.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] At first, the DH rule was not applied to the World Series.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] From 1973 to 1975, all World Series games were played under National League rules, with no DH and with pitchers required to bat.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] For 1976, it was decided the DH rule would apply to all games in the World Series, regardless of venue, but only in even-numbered years.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Cincinnati Reds first baseman Dan Driessen became the first National League designated hitter in the postseason; he was the DH in all four World Series games that year.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Beginning in the 1986 World Series, the DH rule was used in games played in the stadium of the American League representative.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] There was initially no DH in the All-Star Game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Beginning in 1989, the rule was applied only to games played in American League stadiums.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] During this era, if the All-Star Game was scheduled for an American League stadium, fans would vote for the DH for the American League's starting lineup, while the National League's manager decided that league's starting DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Since 2010, the designated hitter has been used by both teams, regardless of where the game is played.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] This was because in the non-DH games, pitchers would rarely actually bat and would usually be replaced by pinch hitters.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Since the National League now uses the DH, it is included in the All-Star voting similar to how it had already been included in American League voting.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] For the 2021 All-Star Game, MLB granted an exception to the DH rule because Los Angeles Angels' Shohei Ohtani was selected as both starting DH and starting pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Ohtani started the game as both a pitcher and the DH and was replaced as pitcher after one inning but remained in the game as the DH without the American League having to forfeit the use of a DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The American League would have lost the DH if either Ohtani, or a player replacing him at DH, had played a position in the field other than pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The rationale for the designated hitter rule arose early in the history of professional baseball.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] During the 1880s, an increased emphasis on improving the specialized skill of pitching contributed to a decline in pitcher batting averages.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 1891, during negotiations surrounding the merger of the American Association and National League, team executives J.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Walter Spalding of New York and William Chase Temple of Pittsburgh proposed competing ideas to eliminate the pitcher from the batting order.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Temple's proposal "favored the substitution of another man to take the pitcher's place at the bat when it came his turn to go there," while Spalding proposed removing the pitcher's turn from the batting order, reducing its length to eight players.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Temple's proposal was voted down by a narrow margin prior to the 1892 season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The idea of a designated hitter was raised by Philadelphia Athletics manager Connie Mack in 1906; however, his proposal received little support.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Pitchers rejected the idea of giving up hitting.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Several managers were interested in the idea and intended to implement it during spring training in 1929.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, Heydler's proposal was not adopted as an official rule change, and he advised teams to have pitchers bat during spring training in order for them to prepare for the regular season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Serious momentum to implement the designated hitter was absent until the pitching dominance of the late 1960s.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 1968, Bob Gibson led the major leagues with a live-ball era record 1.12 ERA.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] For the first time since 1908, the American and National Leagues had a collective batting average below .240; Carl Yastrzemski led the American League in hitting with only a .301 mark.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] After the season, in order to increase offensive output, the height of the pitcher's mound was reduced from 15 to 10 inches (38 to 25 cm), and the upper limit of the strike zone was lowered from the top of a batter's shoulders to his armpits.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 1969, the International League and four other minor leagues began a four-year trial period for the designated hitter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The American League allowed its use in spring training in 1971, however, when the minor league trial period ended, the American and National Leagues could not agree on implementation.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Like other experimental baseball rule changes of the 1960s and 1970s, the DH was embraced by Oakland Athletics owner Charlie O.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] On January 11, 1973, Finley and the other American League owners voted 8–4 to approve the designated hitter for a three-year trial run.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The National League chose not to implement the DH; it was intended for the two leagues to agree on a common rule at the end of the American League's trial.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] On April 6, 1973, Ron Blomberg of the New York Yankees became the first designated hitter in MLB history, facing Boston Red Sox right-hander Luis Tiant in his first plate appearance.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Blomberg was walked on five pitches with the bases loaded in the first inning.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] As expected, the American League posted a higher batting average than the National League in 1973.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] This trend held in every season in which the American League employed the designated hitter but the National League did not between 1973 and 2021.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] At the end of its three-year trial period, the American League kept the designated hitter, while the National League still refused to adopt it.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In response to increases in American League attendance because of the DH, the National League held a vote on August 13, 1980, to determine whether or not to adopt it.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] A majority of the 12 member teams was necessary to pass the rule, and the measure was expected to pass.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, when the teams were informed that the rule would not take effect until the 1982 season, Philadelphia Phillies vice president Bill Giles was unsure of how the team owner, Ruly Carpenter, wanted him to vote.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Unable to contact Carpenter, who was on a fishing trip, Giles was forced to abstain from voting.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Prior to the meeting, Harding Peterson, general manager for the Pittsburgh Pirates, was told to side with the Phillies however they voted.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The final tally was four teams voting for the DH (the Atlanta Braves, New York Mets, St.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Louis Cardinals, and San Diego Padres), five votes against (the Chicago Cubs, Cincinnati Reds, Los Angeles Dodgers, Montreal Expos, and San Francisco Giants), and three abstentions (the Phillies, Pirates, and Houston Astros).
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Five days after that meeting, the Cardinals fired their general manager, John Claiborne, who was the leading proponent for the adoption of the DH rule, and the National League never held another vote on the issue.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The designated hitter was not used in the World Series from 1973 to 1975.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Between 1976 and 1985, the DH was used in the World Series during even-numbered years, while pitchers batted in odd-numbered years.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 1986, the rule was changed to implement designated hitters only in World Series games in which the home team was from the American League.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] This rule was also adopted for interleague play during the regular season upon its introduction in 1997.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] As time passed, the designated hitter rule enabled American League managers to employ diverse strategies in setting their teams' lineups.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Managers could rotate the DH role among part-time players (for example, using a left-handed batter against a right-handed pitcher and vice versa), or they could employ a full-time designated hitter against all pitchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Healthy regular lineup players gained the ability to take a partial day off by not playing the field, while aging, injured, and injury prone players gained the opportunity to bat without being exposed to re-injury while fielding.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] By 2009, only a handful of players compiled over 400 at-bats as a DH each year.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] This trend continued, even with the eventual onset of the universal designated hitter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The Astros moved to the American League in 2013, giving each league 15 teams and requiring interleague play throughout the entire season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] There was debate within MLB to unify the rules of the two leagues, with either the American League returning to its pre-1973 rules and having the pitcher hit or the National League adopting the DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In January 2016, MLB commissioner Rob Manfred indicated that consideration was given to the National League adopting the DH for the 2017 season, when a new collective bargaining agreement would take effect.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, he later backtracked, saying that he did not envision such a change being made in the near future.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Accordingly, the DH rule was not then adopted by the National League.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2020, in an attempt to avoid overtaxing pitchers and lessen the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic, the National League used the DH for the first time.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] For the first time since 1972 (the final year before the American League adopted the DH), the National League had the higher seasonal batting average of the two leagues.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] At least one of the proposals released during negotiations between MLB and the Major League Baseball Players' Association (MLBPA) regarding the 2021 season's rules included the so-called "universal DH," but an impasse led to a temporary return to National League pitchers hitting in that year.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] On April 4, 2021, an American League team voluntarily declined to use a designated hitter in their starting lineup for the first time since 1976, when the Los Angeles Angels placed starting pitcher Shohei Ohtani second in the batting order.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] This was also the first time since 1903 that a pitcher had been listed as the second hitter in the starting lineup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] On June 23, 2021, Ohtani made history again when, for the first time, an AL team did not use the designated hitter and an NL team did.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] While the Angels declined the DH privilege, the visiting Giants opted to use it, starting Alex Dickerson at DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] On February 10, 2022, Manfred announced plans for a universal DH beginning with the 2022 season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The rule was ratified as part of a new collective bargaining agreement with the MLBPA on March 10, 2022, after which both leagues have continuously employed the designated hitter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The designated hitter rule has been the subject of debate both before and after its implementation.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Supporters of the rule have cited its original intent, to replace weak-hitting pitchers in the batting order, and the potential for added excitement due to the associated increase in offense.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Critics have cited the asymmetry of creating a position that is not required to hit and field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Older players who are weak fielders or have a history of injuries have been able to extend their careers by becoming designated hitters, as the position is less physically demanding than those that involve playing the field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The designated hitter rule also changes managerial strategy, particularly in late innings.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Without the DH, a manager must decide whether to let a pitcher bat or to substitute a pinch hitter.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If a pinch hitter is used, then the manager must decide whether that hitter will stay in the game after batting, and if so, at what position.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] When the decision to remove a pitcher is made, the manager may also use the double switch, a substitution mechanism in which the new pitcher adopts a different position in the batting order than the previous pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The double switch is typically employed to delay the new pitcher's first plate appearance.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The designated hitter reduces the need for late-inning pinch hitters and eliminates the principal utility of the double switch entirely.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Prior to the introduction of the universal DH, interleague play caused teams to adjust their usual strategies for lineup and roster construction.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 1993, John Olerud, who had won that year's American League batting title, was benched in the third game of the World Series, played in a National League stadium, when designated hitter Paul Molitor took Olerud's typical position at first base.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2003, ESPN writer Jayson Stark claimed that the San Francisco Giants may have lost the previous year's World Series because their roster was not optimized for the use of a DH in the home stadium of their American League opponents.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Similarly, after the Central League champion Yomiuri Giants were swept in the 2019 Japan Series, manager Tatsunori Hara said that the addition of the designated hitter gave teams in the Pacific League an advantage when developing pitchers.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] When regular season interleague play was introduced to Major League Baseball, multiple proposals were made to remove the DH from the American League in order to maintain consistency across both leagues.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Until the introduction of the universal DH, the American League held a distinct advantage over the National League during interleague play in most seasons.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The ability of American League teams to increase the depth of their lineups with designated hitters contributed to this trend.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] When the games were played in AL parks, the NL team had to put a bench player into the lineup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] When the games were played in NL parks, even though the AL team had to take a player out of their lineup, that left them with a starting player available to pinch-hit and/or come in as a substitute player later in the game, as opposed to a bench player on the NL team.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Occasionally, injuries sustained by pitchers were cited to support the expansion of the DH to the National League.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2008, New York Yankees pitcher Chien-Ming Wang was injured while running the bases in an interleague game against the Houston Astros.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Wang was diagnosed with a torn Lisfranc ligament and a partial tear of the peroneus longus of the right foot.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Wang's subsequent extensive rehabilitation prevented him from being an effective major league pitcher after the injury.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] He subsequently said that while he enjoyed hitting, he favored consistency between the leagues, remarking, "Who would people rather see, a real hitter hitting home runs or a pitcher swinging a wet newspaper?
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The Baseball Writers' Association of America presents an annual award to the outstanding designated hitter of the season, called the Edgar Martínez Award.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Renamed for the former Seattle Mariners DH after his retirement in 2004, the award was introduced in 1973 and has been given every season since, except 1994 due to the players' strike.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Multiple winners include David Ortiz (eight times), Martínez (five times), and Shohei Ohtani (four times).
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] DHs have generally not had much impact on the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award or National Baseball Hall of Fame voting, because of the relative rarity of the full-time DH and the DH not contributing defense.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2021, Shohei Ohtani became the first everyday DH to win league MVP honors, having played in 126 of 155 games (81.29%) at DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, Ohtani's MVP season was mainly due to his success as a two-way player, having also logged 23 games as a pitcher and seven games in the outfield.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2023, Ohtani won his second MVP award, playing 134 of 135 games as a DH that season while also pitching in 23 of those games.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2024, Ohtani, now with the Los Angeles Dodgers in the National League, won his second consecutive MVP award, the first time the award was given to a player who exclusively played as a DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Due to Tommy John surgery on his pitching elbow, Ohtani only played as a DH in 2024.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Ohtani won his third consecutive MVP award in 2025, returning to two-way form with 47 innings in 14 starts as a pitcher in addition to 158 appearances as a DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] During the 1993 season Paul Molitor became the first player to win the World Series Most Valuable Player Award, while playing 137 of 160 games (85.63%) as a DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Hideki Matsui (2009), David Ortiz (2013), and Jorge Soler (2021) were the only other DHs to win World Series MVP.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Soler, playing for the Atlanta Braves, was the only DH to win the award while a member of a National League team.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In games played at National League parks, Ortiz and Molitor played at first base, while Soler played in right field.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, Matsui became the only World Series MVP to never play in the field that season, as he came in as a pinch hitter in the pitcher's spot but was never moved to a fielding position via a double switch during games played in a National League park.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Ortiz was also the first designated hitter to win the ALCS MVP in 2004, followed by Delmon Young in 2012, and Yordan Alvarez in 2021.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2025, Shohei Ohtani became the first designated hitter to win NLCS MVP, though he also appeared in six innings as a pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Among Hall of Famers, Paul Molitor and Jim Rice were, until 2014, the only inductees to even have played at least 25% of their games at DH, though Molitor played more games at DH than any other position during his career.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2014, Frank Thomas became the first Hall of Famer who played the majority of his games at DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2019, Edgar Martínez and Harold Baines were inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Martinez played over 70% of his games at DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Baines played more than half of his games at DH, playing only 63 games in the field between 1989 and the end of his career in 2001.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2022, David Ortiz became the first full-time DH to be elected to the Hall of Fame on his first ballot.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Prior to 2020, only one designated hitter Silver Slugger Award was awarded, and only American League players were the recipients due to the National League awarding a pitcher Silver Slugger Award.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2020, and since 2022, both American and National Leagues began awarding Silver Slugger Awards for designated hitters.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The first National League DH Silver Slugger Award was given to Marcell Ozuna in 2020.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Martinez became the first and to date only player to win two Silver Slugger Awards in the same season, winning as both a designated hitter and a left fielder.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Japan's Pacific League adopted the designated hitter in 1975, two years after its adoption in the American League.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Japan's Central League has not adopted the designated hitter – the only top-level professional league in the world to refrain from doing so.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In August 2025, the six owners of Central League teams unanimously voted to adopt the DH beginning in 2027.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] When teams from different leagues play against each other in interleague games or the Japan Series, the DH rule is currently adopted if the Pacific League's team hosts the game, similar to the MLB rules before the universal DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The Mexican League introduced the designated hitter in 1974, one year after the American League.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The Cuban National Series adopted the designated hitter in 1977.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The KBO League introduced the designated hitter in 1982.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The DH is used for all Minor League Baseball (MiLB) games.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Prior to the adoption of the DH by the National League in 2022, only Rookie and Single-A level leagues used the DH rule in all games, while Double-A and Triple-A games, when both teams were National League affiliates the designated hitter was not used.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The reason for the difference was that as players get closer to reaching the majors, teams preferred to have the rules mimic those of the major league teams for which the players may soon be playing.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The Atlantic League, an independent minor league that became an MLB Partner League after the 2021 MiLB reorganization, implemented an experimental "double-hook rule" for its 2021 season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Under this rule, once a team removes its starting pitcher it loses the right to use a DH for the rest of the game.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The "double hook" rule was modified for the 2022 Atlantic League season.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] The change allows a team whose starting pitcher goes at least five innings to keep its DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In American high schools and other amateur baseball leagues that use National Federation of State High School Associations (NFHS) rules, a DH may bat in place of one player in any position, not just a pitcher.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Many coaches use a designated hitter in place of the weakest hitter in the lineup, if they use one at all.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In amateur baseball, many pitchers are also good hitters and will often play another position (or even DH) when not pitching.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In 2020, NFHS rules were modified to also add a "Player/DH" rule where a player may start the game with offensive and defensive roles, and be substituted out only on defense while remaining in the game on offense as a DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Japanese high school baseball was, for a long time, one of the few amateur baseball leagues in the world to never use the designated hitter rule at all.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] It was not until the 2026 rulebook update that the designated hitter rule was introduced, with the 2026 Spring Koshien tournament being the first major tournament to adopt the rule.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In high school baseball in South Korea, the rule has been adopted since 2004.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] American Legion rules, on the other hand, allow the DH only to bat for the pitcher; prior to 1995, the use of the DH was not allowed in Legion baseball at all.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In college baseball, NCAA rules state that the designated hitter must hit for the pitcher, but in many instances the pitcher is also a good hitter, and the coach may elect to let the pitcher bat in the lineup.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] If the pitcher opts to bat for himself, he is treated as two separate positions – a pitcher and a designated hitter (abbreviated P/DH on the lineup card) – and may be substituted for as such (i.e. if he is removed as the pitcher, he may remain as the designated hitter and vice versa).
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] Conversely, a player who begins the game as the DH, but not as the pitcher, may come into the game as a reliever and remain as the DH (in effect becoming a P/DH), be relieved on the mound later in the game but continue to bat as the DH.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] In Little League Baseball, the DH is not used except in the Senior League (age 15–16) division, where the DH can bat in place of any defensive player.
[src:defensive-spectrum/designated-hitter] However, a league may adopt a rule which requires all players present and able to play to be listed in the batting order (such that the order contains more than nine players), and thus all players will have a turn to bat even when they are not assigned a fielding position.
